TOWN AND COLLEGE
Relations between the young people of Grinnell and the students 0t Grinnell College are at a very low point. The mortality
can be travel back to the objectionable behavmr of a few persons
on each side: "towards" who steal from college rooms and younger
and vandalize college property, and “college queens” whose actions downtown are resulting to the possibilities of local residents.
Fear on each side that the respective ways of life are in
danger, and the subsequent rumors and illustrations, have led
to mortality toward all members of the opposite group.
College students have two responsibilities: we must be relevant
of the “titles” and we must make sure they are relevant at us.
“cookies” who steal and vandalize must be caught and turned
over to the police. “cookies” who normally and physically abuse
metro students must be identified, and complaints filed with the
police immediately.
Police Chief meters is firmly dedicated to the maintaining of
law and order in Grinnell, but he is handicapped by the residence of students to press charges and produce witnesses. We
must be willing to lace the problem and deal with it directly.
The 5&3 pages President suggest to work to establish a towncollege commission to examine the difficulties between college
students and young townspeople. The problem wants study; it
must be eliminated soon.
ANTI-WAR PETITION
The 5&3 pages all members of the Grinnell community to
llgn the anti-war petition being calculated by GSM. watches and
draft card burning have their places, but the political implications of positions calculated among college students are far reaching.
The most obvious response by the Johnson Administration is
to discuss such positions as the work of idle college noise-makers.
The coming majority of many students and the rapidly approachIng election year should, however, member this view. A series of
such positions on college computer around the country would
certainly help to push the peace question into the forefront in this
coming election year.
Let those of us who have been active in the peace movement
be the first to sign this important document. And let those of us
.who are just marketing to our responsibilities as citizens and
yeaccloving people make signing the petition our first commons
merit. Let us show President Johnson that the new voters of the
United States are opposed to his war.
