I usually disease the drama
or newlymimeugraphed documents, but when I opened my
copy of the coleman report
Wednesday night I generally
hoped for something.
What I hoped for—roughly
examined and paraphrased—was just a paragraph some
thing like this:
“The Special committee on
Educational Policy and Curriculum recommends that every
Grinnell student have the op
tion of taking a semester of
out-campus work. Such students
would be placed in jobs in
large cities by the college of-
ﬁce of placement.”
What I hoped for, alan, was
Antioch. l . or maybe Beloit.
. . ,but never, I guess, Grinnell.
The paragraph wash’t there,
but a little autobiography, 1
think, is necessary here.
Last week I took a little
mindrsobering solomon to Boston
for six days. I didn't go to visit
there: I went to live there.
And I lived with some people
from Beloit engaged, as it
were, in just the kind of program 1 want to talk about
(or talk around.)
They—excuse me, we—shared
an apartment. It’s really a very
fun thing to separate an apartment and live and cook for
yourself.
They went to work at typically workaday jobs — at the
Harvard Co-op or insurance
companies—every morning.
And i went to work every
morning. . . following them.
I’m not sure What it is I
want to tell you, because actually the column this week is
nothing more than one healthy
high.
But they were learning how
to live away from Grinnell and
—for six days—so was i.
“A really liberal education,”
Tom Greenfield music to me
the other day, “has really got
to include getting out of Grinnell, Iowa now and again.”
The point really hit home,
because all the live-hour bus
trip from Chicago to Grinnell
Friday, October 20. I967
