After awkwardly growing in
my last two articles for some
kind of grand catherine of city
and caused. I thought in this
third and final article of the
Dr. village biology I would appeal to the intellectual that
links in all of us somewhere
between nursing and the North
Lounge. I want to examine the
medical problem at Grinnell
and do What most critics actor
doing—suggest a possible soiuflorid
The main problem with Grin<
hell's medical help is that the
college has little or no control
over‘it. If the student is opportunity enough to contract
more than a cold, he is referred by the health center to
any one of several town doctors who somehow have been
appreciated a share in the student business. That doctor may
or may not be competent but
in any event he examines the
student and then applies to the
insurance company that carries
the college health insurance and
receives from it a standard
fee. (In one case two years
ago the fee was eight dollars
for two minutes' time; the time
was issueﬁevent.)
The student receives a receipt from the insurance coming and the case is closed.
n other words. the town doctor, always busy with his town
patients who provide the bulk
of his business and are an unfortunately important part of
his income, can nevertheless
in a year’s time accrue a
healthy—is that the word?—
parliamentary income from his
student patients. And with that
side business. that fixed income
that no one will ever question,
there is always the reputation.
whether realized or not, to
slight students and spend more
time with that plastic portion
